ENCEPHALITIS - PHILIPPINES: (SULTAN KUDARAT) HORSEMEAT SUSPECTED, FATAL, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
************************************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 14 May 2014
Source: Interaksyon, Philippines News Agency report [edited]
http://interaksyon.com/article/86807/deadly-horse-meat--us-japanese-labs-help-sought-in-poisoning-death-of-7-s--kudarat-residents


The Department of Health (DOH) in Region 12 [SOCCSKSARGEN] has sought the assistance of laboratories in the USA and Japan to determine the cause of the deaths in April 2014 of 7 people in Senator Ninoy Aquino town in Sultan Kudarat province, who were initially believed to have consumed contaminated horse meat. Dr Teogenes Baluma, DOH Region 12 director, said they sent some samples earlier taken from the 7 victims to the American CDC in Georgia, and to another laboratory facility in Japan for examination and analysis.

"We don't have definitive findings yet as to the actual cause of the deaths but we're hoping that these laboratory examinations can provide us some answers," he said in a radio interview. The official said the samples comprised spinal fluid and blood specimens of the 7 victims, all residents of Sitio Parreno, Barangay Tinalon in Senator Ninoy Aquino town. The victims succumbed to severe poisoning symptoms several days after eating the entrails and meat of several horses that died of unknown causes.

Baluma said they sought the assistance of the US and Japan laboratories owing to the limited capability of local facilities. "We want to be really certain as to what caused their deaths so we can properly manage the treatment of the other victims and possible similar cases in the future," he said. Based on the agency's initial analysis on the signs and symptoms experienced by the 7 fatalities and other victims who were hospitalized, he said it appears that it was caused by the viral encephalitis disease.

Nestor Casador, Sultan Kudarat provincial agriculturist, earlier said the victims fell ill after consuming the meat of 3 horses that were slaughtered after turning weak and eventually died from unknown causes. Citing a report from their veterinary unit, he said 5 of the victims died several days after eating the entrails of the horses.

Baluma said no new cases of the disease have so far emerged in the affected area and all local residents who were earlier hospitalized have already recovered. "We have continuing interventions like antibiotic treatments for residents who were hospitalized and had close contact with the victims," he said.

